{
    // Node debugging for the TypeScript workspace (ts/). Notes, all verified
    // over CDP rather than assumed:
    //
    //  1. No tsx. Node runs .ts directly via native type stripping. Debugging a
    //     demo or a core test needs no build: the file you break in is stripped
    //     in place. The one caveat is cross-package code — a demo imports the
    //     BUILT @ilmek/core (packages/core/dist), so `pnpm build` once before
    //     stepping INTO core; the demo's own frames never need it. Core's own
    //     tests import ../src relative, so they stay build-free.
    //  2. Positions are exact. Type stripping replaces types with whitespace
    //     rather than rewriting code, so a breakpoint on a line of real code
    //     resolves to that line, scopes populate, and Debug Console expressions
    //     read real source names. Stepping into built core resolves through its
    //     sourceMap back to packages/core/src. BUT — see "breakpoints that move"
    //     below. Whitespace is the trick AND the trap.
    //  3. --test-isolation=none for the test configs. `node --test` normally
    //     runs each file in a CHILD process (NODE_TEST_CONTEXT=child-v8);
    //     isolation=none keeps them in the process VSCode launched, so
    //     breakpoints bind without relying on child-process auto-attach.
    //     Caveat: test files then share one process — fine here, since each
    //     test builds its own graph and checkpointer.
    //
    // Type stripping does NOT typecheck. `pnpm check` (build → test → demos)
    // is what proves the workspace; these configs are for inspecting it.
    //
    // ── HITL pauses and the debugger ────────────────────────────────────────
    //
    // ctx.interrupt() halts a task by throwing InterruptSignal, which the engine
    // catches as ordinary control flow. To V8 that is still a throw — and since
    // ctx.interrupt() is async, it surfaces as a *promiseRejection*. Two knobs,
    // pulling opposite ways:
    //
    //  • STOP ON PAUSES, AND NOTHING ELSE → the "break on every HITL pause"
    //    config below. Sets ILMEK_DEBUG_BREAK_ON_INTERRUPT=1, which arms a
    //    `debugger` statement in ts/packages/core/src/context.ts right where the pause is
    //    journaled. `full` (the journal key) and `payload` (the question) are in
    //    scope. Inert without the env var, so it costs nothing in production.
    //
    //  • STOP ON REAL ERRORS, BUT NOT ON PAUSES → if you tick "Caught
    //    Exceptions" in the Breakpoints pane, it stops on EVERY HITL pause,
    //    drowning the errors you turned it on for. Filter them out: right-click
    //    "Caught Exceptions" → Edit Condition → paste
    //
    //        !error?.isIlmekInterrupt
    //
    //    `instanceof InterruptSignal` will NOT work there — the condition is
    //    evaluated in the paused frame, where ilmek's exports are out of scope.
    //    That is exactly why InterruptSignal carries a plain `isIlmekInterrupt`
    //    property instead of relying on its class.
    //
    //  Measured, so you do not try it: `skipFiles` does NOT suppress this. It
    //  compiles to V8 blackboxing, and blackboxing a file still pauses on the
    //  exceptions thrown inside it. The condition is the only filter.
    //
    // ── breakpoints that move ───────────────────────────────────────────────
    //
    // Type stripping erases types to WHITESPACE. A comment, an `import type`, an
    // `interface` body — after stripping, those lines hold no executable code at
    // all. A breakpoint on one does not fail; it silently SLIDES FORWARD to the
    // next real statement. Measured on examples/checkout.ts:
    //
    //     asked → resolved
    //      34   →  45   (inside `interface Order` — erased)
    //      37   →  45   (blank line)
    //      39   →  45   (inside `interface Question` — erased)
    //
    // The corollary that actually bites: everything above a module's first
    // statement — the comment header, the whole import block — is erased, so a
    // stale breakpoint anywhere up there lands on that first statement and looks
    // like "the debugger stops for no reason on line 31".
    //
    // If a breakpoint stops somewhere senseless, it is stale. Clear all
    // breakpoints (Breakpoints pane → Remove All) and set them again on lines
    // that survive stripping.
    "version": "0.2.0",
    "configurations": [
        {
            // Answer at the prompt: "evet" charges, "hayır" cancels.
            // integratedTerminal is required — stdin does not exist in the
            // Debug Console, and the demo would hang on its first question.
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "Demo: checkout (interactive)",
            "program": "${workspaceFolder}/ts/examples/checkout.ts",
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            // Same run, scripted "evet". No stdin, deterministic, exit 0/1 —
            // this is the one to step through.
            //
            // Put a breakpoint on the ctx.step("create_order", …) line AND on
            // the ctx.step("charge", …) line below the pause, then walk both
            // runs: on run 2 the node re-enters from the top and the debugger
            // steps straight OVER create_order's callback. That is the journal
            // (MODEL.md §5) with a stack trace attached.
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "Demo: checkout — scripted (selftest)",
            "program": "${workspaceFolder}/ts/examples/checkout.ts",
            "args": ["--selftest"],
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            // Stops in ctx.interrupt() the moment any node pauses for a human —
            // without arming "Caught Exceptions" and its noise. Verified: it
            // stops at context.ts's `debugger` with `full` and `payload` live.
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "Demo: checkout — break on every HITL pause",
            "program": "${workspaceFolder}/ts/examples/checkout.ts",
            "args": ["--selftest"],
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "env": { "ILMEK_DEBUG_BREAK_ON_INTERRUPT": "1" },
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "Demo: streaming (tokens · modes · abort)",
            "program": "${workspaceFolder}/ts/examples/streaming.ts",
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "Demo: map-reduce (send · command · retry)",
            "program": "${workspaceFolder}/ts/examples/mapreduce.ts",
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "TS core tests — all",
            "runtimeExecutable": "node",
            "runtimeArgs": [
                "--test",
                "--test-isolation=none",
                "--test-concurrency=1",
                "packages/core/test/ilmek.test.ts",
                "packages/core/test/spec.test.ts",
                "packages/core/test/stream.test.ts",
                "packages/core/test/control.test.ts"
            ],
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            // Provider tests import the built @ilmek/core — build the workspace
            // (pnpm build) before launching, or run pnpm check.
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "TS checkpointer tests (sqlite + postgres)",
            "runtimeExecutable": "node",
            "runtimeArgs": [
                "--test",
                "--test-isolation=none",
                "--test-concurrency=1",
                "packages/checkpointers/sqlite/test/sqlite.test.ts",
                "packages/checkpointers/postgres/test/postgres.test.ts"
            ],
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "TS tests — current file",
            "runtimeExecutable": "node",
            // ${file}, not ${relativeFile}: the latter is relative to the
            // workspace root ("ts/test/…") while cwd is already ts/, which would
            // send node looking for ts/ts/test/….
            "runtimeArgs": [
                "--test",
                "--test-isolation=none",
                "--test-concurrency=1",
                "${file}"
            ],
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            "type": "node",
            "request": "launch",
            "name": "TS — current file",
            "program": "${file}",
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "console": "integratedTerminal",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        },
        {
            // For a process already started with: node --inspect <file>.ts
            "type": "node",
            "request": "attach",
            "name": "Attach to running node (:9229)",
            "port": 9229,
            "cwd": "${workspaceFolder}/ts",
            "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
        }
    ]
}
